@hotchickheaven I'm not a lawyer but having the formal request on file is also good in case they ever try to terminate you for tangentially related reasons after denying you accommodations.

@hotchickheaven I believe the key is having medical documentation outlining that your current work conditions are unsustainable and supporting specific accommodations. If your employer has an actual HR element, they can have a harder time fighting those.
@hotchickheaven Now there are a million ways to weasel out of fulfilling the full requested accommodation, under the ADA, the employer still risks violating the ADA if they outright refuse.

@hotchickheaven There are a lot of grey areas, but the general idea is that as long as the accom. doesn't interfere with you fulfilling your job description, and it doesn't significantly strain someone else's performance/ budget, the employer has to make an effort under the ADA.

@hotchickheaven I had to request accommodations for my ADHD. I brought my documentation to HR and we set a list of agreeable accommodations. HR then told my supervisor that they had to make an effort as long as it didn't place "undue" hardship on the school.

I'm no longer content to be unobtrusive at the expense of being known. I'm grateful for the language of comics to be that voice for me.

To take up space can be an utterly alien concept when you feel like getting noticed was always another opportunity to be hurt, rejected, "corrected," or belittled. Learning how to start can be painful. It requires abandoning the defense that made me feel safe. Alone, but safe.
Which may all sound very twee but after living for 36 years in constant visceral fear of being observed it feels like finally picking up the shotgun in the video game of emotional validation.

Realizing that I've actually been expressing my inner life through my work by accident for... ever gives me a certain lightness at the opportunity to do it on purpose. To feel seen and not just by accident. To speak with intention.
The next one I wrote as a way of processing some very very old trauma that I've only recently been able to start to name. It scared me and it hurt and I worried about how it would be accepted.

I said as such to my partner who said, I've read your work. I'd say it's deeply personal. 

That came on the heels of realizing my first 2 Hallowzine stories were my way of voicing a deep and spiraling sense of loss.
Several months ago I was reading some heavy autobio comics and was left feeling like I *wished* I could open up like that in my work. To be that vulnerable.

I'm a cartoonist who draws funny animals. If you think you or somebody you care for could be struggling with ADHD:
https://t.co/tTlFzFqihr
A big part of that is going to be re- learning how to live outside of my head and put more of the stories, monsters, and ghosts on paper where they belong.
I've only just started in all this. It's confusing, difficult, and occasionally a bit humiliating. But I'm hopeful that I can put my skills, my energy, and my imagination on a more positive track.

Learning how to see differently is going to be important. Seeing the world as facts that I can interpret rather than impressions distorted by a disregulated internal environment. 
Seeing the offered help and learning to accept it.
The work now is in learning. Learning new ways. Learning from my failures. Learning how to stay that hand that turns my overactive imagination into paranoia, fear, cruelty.

When I'm a character in my own head, and a poorly shaped one, my relationships are reduced to situations without weight. I can't care for the people I love effectively. I can't act sincerely. I lose myself in a skewed narrative that I can't edit or interpret.

Part of the process I'm taking on now in addressing my ADHD, after not knowing or understanding anything about it for 35 years, is trying to untangle that misdirected force. Because that unfocused emotion, anger, fear was breaking my ability function in the actual world.
The same "hand" that leads me into worlds I wish existed can sit on my brain and turn the one I live in into a ghost story.
The anxiety and the reflex to hide builds walls, turns the people I know  into strangers in afraid of, and tells me a thousand stories that aren't true.

One of the hardest things I experience regularly
 is knowing my mind can build wonderful things, bizarre characters,  tell very good stories, but I have a conditioned response to turn that inside out.
